T1  - TV, CELL PHONES AND SOCIAL JUSTICE: A HISTORICAL ANALYSIS OF HOW VIDEO CREATES SOCIAL CHANGE
AN  - 2119846729
AB  - During a 1987 symposium on the media's coverage of the civil rights movement, House of Representatives member John Lewis noted "the civil rights movement would have been like a bird without wings if it hadn't been for the news media" (Treadwell, 1987). Lewis continued by characterizing the media as "sympathetic referees" in the battle against racism and segregation (Treadwell, 1987). Lewis's Congressional website posted an editorial published in Newsweek that noted that "it took members of the press who dared to use their cameras, their pads and their pens to tell the story" of the murder, church bombings, lynching, and countless numbers of brutal attacks against African-Americans in the struggle for civil rights (Lewis, 2009). Over the past sixty years, video has been an important tool in the fight for civil rights and social justice. This paper highlights key moments in history where video played a significant role in documenting institutional racism and civil rights violations. Additionally, this essay will discuss how video has mobilized efforts for civil rights and social justice. As the struggle for social justice and equal protection under the law continues in the 21st century, new media tools are serving as referees against unlawful arrests and violence used against people of color and disadvantaged populations. Cell phones and social media in the hands of citizen journalists have replaced the "cameras, pads, and pens" used by professional reporters to document civil rights violations. Bystanders used cell phones to capture the choking of Eric Garner and the shooting of Walter Scott, among other incidents, across the country. Video of these incidents were critical in providing a visual record of confrontations with law enforcement and sparking debate over issues associated with policing and race relations. At the same time, video posted on social media and broadcast on national television has been instrumental in mobilizing efforts to fight for equal protection under the law, holding law enforcement officials accountable for their actions, and raising public awareness about injustice in America.
